postcontent:
Located in MT. 
Will ship insured with tracking number to you.
No trades. need cash.

Comes without magazine.

Okay, now the build details:
Built by Turbothis AKA MYguns. 
US-made Turbothis receiver.
Tapco G2 FCG.
US made slant brake.
Chinese chrome-lined and threaded (14X1LH) MAK90 barrel, GB and FSB with bayo lugs ground off.
Red Bakelite Chinese furniture, hanguards, pistol grip and sidefolder.
Sidefolder has included cleaning kit inside (hard to find I believe).

Problems: 
Receiver is blued, looks better than pictures show (coming in next post in a few hours), but it is very thin bluing, I went with a paki-build on it so wanted it thin to see the inner rail welds,etc. and the bluing didn't take around a couple rivets.

Dustcover is too short. It "fits" but sortof wedges and isn't easy to pop off. 

Dustcover and gas tube are dark thick bluing VS the thin bluing on receiver.


Overall, I love this gun. Shoots great, has nice heft and haven't had a hiccup with it.


I am wanting $1100. That includes insurance and tracking. I think it's very close to fair, full-on 56S sidefolders are going for around $2400. This includes an original Chinese CL barrel, Turbothis receiver and bakelite furniture. I've seen the furniture sell for $600 itself.

postcontent: In very good condition, minor use and works like new. Reliability, versatility, and value make the Model 2000 the ideal semi-auto shotgun. Inside the Stoeger Model 2000 semi-auto shotgun is the Inertia-Driven operating system, the heart of the world's most prestigious and reliable autoloaders. The Inertia Driven system has only three moving parts in the bolt, the inertia spring, the bolt body, and the rotating locking head, for more reliable operation. The operating system is mostly contained in the receiver, giving the Model 2000 a trimmer forend with better balance. The Stoeger Model 2000 fires everything from 1-1/8 ounce field and target loads to the heaviest 3" waterfowl loads without adjustments. Plus, with no propellant gas venting into the operating system, the Model 2000 stays cleaner. The bolt assembly includes an inertia spring and a rotating locking head and a cavity is designed into the butt stock of the Model 2000 to allow installation of an optional, mercury-filled recoil reducer. This shotgun features a Realtree Max-5 camo finish, a ventilated rib, a white bar front sight, a cross-bolt safety, and a cylinder choke tube. title: For Sale:  SOLD : US H. Aston 1846 Model 1842 .54 Cal. Percussion Pistol
postcontent:
Produced by H. Aston of Middletown, Connecticut. Aston and Ira Johnson, both of Middletown and the Palmetto Armory of Columbia, SC, produced some 24,000 of these fine horse pistols from 1845 through 1852.

This US Henry Aston 1846 Model 1842 .54 caliber single shot smooth bore percussion pistol retains about 10% of its metal finish. The barrel is almost all white, with a mottled appearance and scattered erosion. The hammer and lock plates have a thick patina over some old erosion. The action functions correctly and the spring is strong. The original swivel hinge and steel ramrod with a button-shaped head is complete and functioning. The bore is surface rusted. There is no severe pitting. The brass hardware shows a few dings and depressions, with a mild darkening. The markings are legible. Overall, this handgun is in good, unmolested condition. This is an acceptable example of an early Martial arm. 

The right lock plate is marked "U.S. / H. ASTON" in front of the hammer and "MIDDtn / CONN. 1846" behind the hammer. The trigger guard, backstrap and stock hardware are marked "H". Overall length is 14” with an 8.5" barrel. The left side of barrel is marked “US GWH P” with “1846” on rear top. There are two government inspection oval cartouches on the left side of stock. The front sight is a brass blade. There is NSN.

The pistol is at our shop on consignment, so we are unable to consider trades. No FFL required***Antique black powder.  Shipping is available for an additional charge.

title: For Sale:  Colt 1911
postcontent:
As did every other combatant nation at the onset of the First World War, Britain suffered from arms shortages and began placing orders with American companies to help take up the slack. In 1912, the British started purchasing some 1911 pistols from Colt. With the outbreak of hostilities, it was decided to purchase additional pistols and by 1919 in excess of 17,000 had been delivered. Pistols in both .45 ACP and .455 Auto Mark I were obtained. The former were marked with a "C" serial number prefix while the latter had a "W" prefix. 
This 1911 serial # C-4649 caliber 45 acp was made is 1913 and a letter from the Colt archives states it was one of 20 pistols shipped to the London Armory Company on May 4, 1914. This was prior to the opening shots of the War which occurred on July 28, 1914. This pistol undoubtedly saw service in the hands of a British Officer during the Great War!
The frame and slide have the British proofs. The over all finish is about 30% with the trigger, hammer, slide release and safety showing about 50% of the nitre blue finish. Barrel is marked HS on the lug and the letter P. Rifling is excellent! Grips are in good shape for a 101 year old War veteran. The magazine is a two tone correct punch and saw cut with lanyard loop.
With the approaching anniversary of the start of the Great War July 28,1914 - November 11, 1918 this is your opportunity to own a piece of history. While it has not been researched yet it may be possible to discover which British Officer carried this pistol adding to the collectible and increasing the value!
The Colt letter verifying the shipment information is included
June 28,2014 is the 100 year Anniversary the start of WWI.Sure this fine Colt was involved.

title: For Sale:  .30 M1 Carbine Rimfire Copy Chiappa .22 LR model M122 Citadel Authentic Dimensions with 2 10 Shot Magazines NIB
postcontent:
Our # LGCIR22M1W

Here is the first authentic looking Rimfire copy of the venerable U.S. .30 M1 Carbine to hit the market since Erma’s and Iver Johnson’s demise 25 years ago. Manufacturer is Chiappa Firearms Ltd. / Kimar Plant in Brescia, Italy. Importer is Legacy Sport International of Nevada. Distributor and Warrantor is Chiappa Firearms of Dayton, OH. Service address 6785 West Third Street, Zip 45417, and that address is on the back of the instruction manual. Construction is a two piece sleeved steel 18 inch 1:16 rifling barrel; steel bolt and hammer and springs; polymer receiver; plymer operating handle and trigger group; polymer rear aperture sight with steel screws for windage and elevation adjustmet; polymer collar type post front sight; polymer magazines; polymer barrel band and bayonet lug; zinc alloy trigger; and dark stained Italian hardwood stock that holds a steel butt plate. This rifle is cosmetically faithful to the U.S. Carbine. Its only departure that is readily conspicuous is the grooved receiver that is capable of holding 3/8 base scope mounts, and that is an advantage. Overall length is 35 inches, with a 13 1/8 length of pull on the Buttstock. Weight empty is 4 pounds 8 ounces with center of gravity at the magazine. Magazines hold 10 rounds of .22 Long Rifle caliber ammunition, and each M1-22 comes with a total of two magazines. This little rifle exceeds its Erma ancestors for looks and balance, and it matches them on performance. We test fired the photo specimen, and got up to 3 consecutive shots on Remington Golden Bullet High Velocity ammunition, and up to 7 consecutive shots on Winchester Super X Copper Coated. That is on a par with the Ermas, from our poor memory. If a person wants better feeding than that, the best thing for a new owner to do, is to get a return authorization and send it to Dayton, perhaps a time or two. This is a looker, after all. If a person wants a shooter, best to stick with the most prolific product from a different factory on Sunapee Street in Newport, New Hampshire. Own the M1-22 in the photos, or one of its identical mates for only $ 329.00. >>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>> $20 flat fee lower 48 states; $60 Alaska, Hawaii or Puerto Rico, UPS Ground or USPS Priority with full insurance coverage. Don’t let your buddies use your account, that kind of thing smells like felony level straw purchase attempt. NO AMEX NO PAYPAL. We accept MC/Visa/Discover/USPS MO paid orders shipped ASAP. 7 day hold on checks. FFL ok by fax, e-mail or mail, please ask your dealer to put your name and Gun Brand on there. 7 day money back on used, no return on New Items, layaway, or ammo. We do not pay transfer fees or return shipping. Lay-away 20% down, balance in 90 days. Phone hours 8:00 – 5:00 CST Mon - Fri CST. Local pickup OK.
